  "abstract": "novel Uncle Tom's Cabin and into her 1859 novel Dred: A Tale of the Great Dismal Swamps.Cholera experiences were sometimes overshadowed by yellow fever outbreaks.As historian Andrew McIlwaine Bell points out, \"no other disease produced more public panic throughout the nineteenth century\" (6).The history of yellow fever and panic is often linked with the concept of contagion as a (narrative) pattern.As Martin Pernick argues, \"[r]eferences to contagious fear were not necessarily or wholly metaphorical\" (861) since fear was seen as a direct cause of disease.It is also reflected in yellow fever narratives, in which fear and \"senselessness with terror\" (Souvestre 51) induce yellow fever.In this line of argument, panic is likened to an \"epidemic of fear\" and also considered the agent that intensifies the speed and extent by which epidemics spread (Pernick 861).Between July and November 1793, about four to five thousand Philadelphia residents, approximately ten percent of the capital city's population, died from yellow fever.Many more left the city for a temporary home in the country.Among them were the infected founder Alexander Hamilton and his wife, and Mathew Carey, who published his Short Account of the Malignant Fever shortly after his return to the city in November 1793.Carey's Short Account is a racialized pamphlet that chronicles the epidemic.In their Narrative of the Proceedings of the Black People during the Late Awful Calamity in Philadelphia in the Year 1793 (1794), Richard Allen and Absalom Jones point out that Carey lacked any firsthand experience and base their main criticism on the fact that he had actually fled the infected city and published his account upon his return.They decry that, despite the services rendered by African Americans during the epidemic, their situation did not improve in its aftermath.Taken together as texts conversing with one another, Carey's Short Account and Jones and Allen's Narrative point to the importance that questions of exclusion, agency, race, and class will continue to play for the nation.Alongside these historical narratives, yellow fever provides a dramatic setting for Charles Brockden Brown's gothic novel Arthur Mervyn, or, Memoirs of the Year 1793 (1799/1800) and is used to represent the complex experience of crisis the young nation was facing.While fiction became the \"carrier zone\" (Samuels 96) to construct the nation, Philadelphia became the microcosm to carry it out.Yellow fever had to be controlled, and the national project was in need of further interpretation and solidification.Brown was one of the writers who took up this interpretational work in the 1790s and-with Arthur Mervyn-put his version of a more hybrid makeup of U.S. society and political ideals against the spread of disease.Philadelphia experienced repeated outbreaks of yellow fever until 1805, and then again in the 1820s.Concurrent epidemics affected New York, Boston, and Baltimore in the early years of the republic.For example, the 1798 epidemic-under the direct influence of which Brown",
